[src:mobile-app-security/application-security] Web Application Security Tools are specialized tools for working with HTTP traffic, e.g., Web application firewalls.
[src:mobile-app-security/application-security] Different approaches will find different subsets of the security vulnerabilities lurking in an application and are most effective at different times in the software lifecycle.
[src:mobile-app-security/application-security] They each represent different tradeoffs of time, effort, cost and vulnerabilities found.
[src:mobile-app-security/application-security] The Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) provides free and open resources.
[src:mobile-app-security/application-security] It is led by a non-profit called The OWASP Foundation.
[src:mobile-app-security/application-security] The OWASP Top 10 - 2017 results from recent research based on comprehensive data compiled from over 40 partner organizations.
[src:mobile-app-security/application-security] This data revealed approximately 2.3 million vulnerabilities across over 50,000 applications.
[src:mobile-app-security/application-security] The OWASP Top 10 Proactive Controls 2024 is a list of security techniques every software architect and developer should know and heed.
[src:mobile-app-security/application-security] Security testing techniques scour for vulnerabilities or security holes in applications.
[src:mobile-app-security/application-security] These vulnerabilities leave applications open to exploitation.
[src:mobile-app-security/application-security] Ideally, security testing is implemented throughout the entire software development life cycle (SDLC) so that vulnerabilities may be addressed in a timely and thorough manner.
[src:mobile-app-security/application-security] There are many kinds of automated tools for identifying vulnerabilities in applications.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] A **mobile app** or **application** is a computer program or software application designed to run on a mobile device such as a smartphone, tablet, or smartwatch.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Mobile applications often stand in contrast to desktop applications which are designed to run on desktop computers, and web applications which run in mobile web browsers rather than directly on the mobile device.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Apps are generally downloaded from app stores, which are a type of digital distribution platforms.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] The term "app", short for "application", has since become very popular; in 2010, it was listed as "Word of the Year" by the American Dialect Society.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Apps are broadly classified into three types: native apps, hybrid apps and web apps.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Native applications are designed specifically for a mobile operating system, typically iOS or Android.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Web apps are written in HTML5 or CSS and typically run through a browser.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Hybrid apps are built using web technologies such as JavaScript, CSS, and HTML5 and function like web apps disguised in a native container.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Most mobile devices are sold with several apps bundled as pre-installed software, such as a web browser, email client, calendar, mapping program, and an app for buying music, other media, or more apps.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Some pre-installed apps can be removed by an ordinary uninstall process, thus leaving more storage space for desired ones.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Where the software does not allow this, some devices can be rooted, jailbroken, or otherwise modified to eliminate the undesired apps.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Users can download non-preinstalled apps from distribution platforms such as app stores.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] These may be operated by the owner of the device's mobile operating system, such as the App Store or Google Play Store; by the device manufacturers, such as the Galaxy Store and Huawei AppGallery; or by third parties, such as the Amazon Appstore and F-Droid.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Usually, they are downloaded from the platform to a target device, but sometimes they can be downloaded to laptops or desktop computers.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Apps can also be installed manually, for example by running an Android application package on Android devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Some apps are freeware, while others have a price, which can be upfront or a subscription.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Some apps also include microtransactions or advertising.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] In any case, the revenue is usually split between the application's creator and the app store.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] The same app can, therefore, cost a different price depending on the mobile platform.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Mobile apps were originally offered for general productivity and information retrieval, including email, calendar, contacts, the stock market and weather information.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] However, public demand and the availability of developer tools drove rapid expansion into other categories, such as those handled by desktop application software packages.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] As with other software, the explosion in number and variety of apps made discovery a challenge, which in turn led to the creation of a wide range of review, recommendation, and curation sources, including blogs, magazines, and dedicated online app-discovery services.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] In 2014 government regulatory agencies began trying to regulate and curate apps, particularly medical apps.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Some companies offer apps as an alternative method to deliver content with certain advantages over an official website.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] With a growing number of mobile applications available at app stores and the improved capabilities of smartphones, people are downloading more applications to their devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Usage of mobile apps has become increasingly prevalent across mobile phone users.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] A May 2012 comScore study reported that during the previous quarter, more mobile subscribers used apps than browsed the web on their devices: 51.1% vs.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Researchers found that usage of mobile apps strongly correlates with user context and depends on user's location and time of the day.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Mobile apps are playing an ever-increasing role within healthcare and when designed and integrated correctly can yield many benefits.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Market research firm Gartner predicted that 102 billion apps would be downloaded in 2013 (91% of them free), which would generate $26 billion in the US, up 44.4% on 2012's US$18 billion.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] By Q2 2015, the Google Play and Apple stores alone generated $5 billion.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] An analyst report estimates that the app economy creates revenues of more than €10 billion per year within the European Union, while over 529,000 jobs have been created in 28 EU states due to the growth of the app market.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Mobile applications may be classified by numerous methods.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] A common scheme is to distinguish native, web-based, and hybrid apps.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] All apps targeted toward a particular mobile platform are known as native apps.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Therefore, an app intended for Apple device does not run on Android devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] As a result, most businesses develop apps for multiple platforms.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] While developing native apps, professionals incorporate best-in-class user interface modules.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] This accounts for better performance, consistency and a good user experience.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Users also benefit from wider access to application programming interfaces and make limitless use of all apps from the particular device.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Further, they also switch over from one app to another effortlessly.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] The main purpose of creating such apps is to ensure the best performance for a specific mobile operating system.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] A web-based app is implemented with the standard web technologies of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Internet access is typically required for proper behavior or being able to use all features compared to offline usage.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Most, if not all, user data is stored in the cloud.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] The performance of these apps is similar to a web application running in a browser, which can be noticeably slower than the equivalent native app.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] It also may not have the same level of features as the native app.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] The concept of the hybrid app is a mix of native and web-based apps.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Apps developed using Apache Cordova, Flutter, Xamarin, React Native, Sencha Touch, and other frameworks fall into this category.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Hybrid apps are made to support web and native technologies across multiple platforms.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] These apps are easier and faster to develop than pure native apps.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Development involves the use of a single codebase that works in multiple mobile operating systems.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Despite such advantages, hybrid apps exhibit lower performance.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Often, apps fail to bear the same look-and-feel in different mobile operating systems.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Developing apps for mobile devices requires considering the constraints and features of these devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Mobile devices run on battery and have less powerful processors than personal computers and also have more features such as location detection and cameras.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Developers also have to consider a wide array of screen sizes, hardware specifications and configurations because of intense competition in mobile software and changes within each of the platforms (although these issues can be overcome with mobile device detection).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Mobile application development requires the use of specialized integrated development environments.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Mobile apps are first tested within the development environment using emulators and later subjected to field testing.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Emulators provide an inexpensive way to test applications on mobile phones to which developers may not have physical access.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Mobile user interface (UI) Design is also essential.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Mobile UI considers constraints and contexts, screen, input and mobility as outlines for design.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] The user is often the focus of interaction with their device, and the interface entails components of both hardware and software.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] User input allows users to manipulate a system, and the device's output allows the system to indicate the effects of the users' manipulation.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Mobile UI design constraints include limited attention and form factors, such as a mobile device's screen size for a user's hand.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Mobile UI contexts signal cues from user activity, such as location and scheduling that can be shown from user interactions within a mobile application.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Overall, mobile UI design's goal is primarily for an understandable, user-friendly interface.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Mobile UIs, or front-ends, rely on mobile back-ends to support access to enterprise systems.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] The mobile back-end facilitates data routing, security, authentication, authorization, working off-line, and service orchestration.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] This functionality is supported by a mix of middleware components including mobile app servers, Mobile Backend as a service (MBaaS), and SOA infrastructure.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Conversational interfaces display the computer interface and present interactions through text instead of graphic elements.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] They emulate conversations with real humans.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] There are two main types of conversational interfaces: voice assistants (like the Amazon Echo) and chatbots.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Conversational interfaces are growing particularly practical as users are starting to feel overwhelmed with mobile apps (a term known as "app fatigue").
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] The three biggest app stores are Google Play for Android, App Store for iOS, and Microsoft Store for Windows and Xbox.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Google Play (formerly known as the Android Market) is an international online software store developed by Google for Android devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] In July 2013, the number of apps downloaded via the Google Play Store surpassed 50 billion, of the over 1 million apps available.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] As of September 2016, according to Statista the number of apps available exceeded 2.4 million.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Over 80% of apps in the Google Play Store are free to download.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] The store generated a revenue of 6 billion U.S. dollars in 2015.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Apple's App Store for iOS and iPadOS was not the first app distribution service, but it ignited the mobile revolution and was opened on July 10, 2008, and as of September 2016, reported over 140 billion downloads.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] The original AppStore was first demonstrated to Steve Jobs in 1993 by Jesse Tayler at NeXTWorld Expo As of June 6, 2011, there were 425,000 apps available, which had been downloaded by 200 million iOS users.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] During Apple's 2012 Worldwide Developers Conference, CEO Tim Cook announced that the App Store has 650,000 available apps to download as well as 30 billion apps downloaded from the app store until that date.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] From an alternative perspective, figures seen in July 2013 by the BBC from tracking service Adeven indicate over two-thirds of apps in the store are "zombies", barely ever installed by consumers.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Microsoft Store (formerly known as the Windows Store) was introduced by Microsoft in 2012 for its Windows 8 and Windows RT platforms.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Mobile application management (MAM) describes software and services responsible for provisioning and controlling access to internally developed and commercially available mobile apps used in business settings.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] The strategy is meant to offset the security risk of a Bring Your Own Device (BYOD) work strategy.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Containerization is an alternate approach to security.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Rather than controlling an employee/s entire device, containerization apps create isolated pockets separate from personal data.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Company control of the device only extends to that separate container.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Especially when employees "bring your own device" (BYOD), mobile apps can be a significant security risk for businesses, because they transfer unprotected sensitive data to the Internet without the knowledge and consent of the users.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Reports of stolen corporate data show how quickly corporate and personal data can fall into the wrong hands.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Data theft is not just the loss of confidential information, but makes companies vulnerable to attack and blackmail.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Professional mobile application management helps companies protect their data.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] One option for securing corporate data is app wrapping.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] But there are also some disadvantages like copyright infringement or the loss of warranty rights.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Functionality, productivity and user experience are particularly limited under app wrapping.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] The policies of a wrapped app can not be changed.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] If required, it must be recreated from scratch, adding cost.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] An app wrapper is a mobile app made wholly from an existing website or platform, with few or no changes made to the underlying application.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] The "wrapper" is essentially a new management layer that allows developers to set up usage policies appropriate for app use.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Examples of these policies include whether or not authentication is required, allowing data to be stored on the device, and enabling/disabling file sharing between users.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Because most app wrappers are often websites first, they often do not align with iOS or Android Developer guidelines.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] Alternatively, it is possible to offer native apps securely through enterprise mobility management.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-app] This enables more flexible IT management as apps can be easily implemented and policies adjusted at any time.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] Mobile application development presents certain security challenges that are unique compared to web applications and other forms of software.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet provides guidance on security considerations for mobile app development.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] It is not a comprehensive guide by any means, but rather a starting point for developers to consider security in their mobile app development.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] For more information, see the Secure Product Design Cheat Sheet.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] Developing with third-party libraries and components introduces the possibility of security unknowns.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] See the Vulnerable Dependency Management Cheat Sheet for recommendations on managing third-party dependencies when vulnerabilities are discovered.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] Authentication is a complex topic and there are many pitfalls.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] Authentication logic must be written and tested with extreme care.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] The tips here are only a starting point and barely scratch the surface.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] For more information, see the Authentication Cheat Sheet and M1: Insecure Authentication/Authorization from the OWASP Mobile Top 10.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] See the Logging Cheat Sheet for examples of data that should not be logged.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] If a Shortcut is assigned to the Action Button (on iPhone 15 Pro and iPhone 16 Pro models), it can be executed by pressing the Action Button while the device is locked.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] If a Shortcut is assigned to the Control Center (on iOS/iPadOS 18+), it can be executed by pulling up the Control Center and pressing the Shortcut button while the device is locked.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] A Shortcut can be invoked via Siri while the device is locked.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] If a Shortcut is added to the user's Home Screen (on iOS/iPadOS 18+), it can be directly executed by tapping the Shortcut button on the user's lock screen while the device is locked.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] If a Shortcut is set to run at a specific interval or a specific time, it can execute even if the device is locked.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] For further reading, visit the OWASP Mobile Top 10 Project.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] For a more detailed framework for mobile security, see the OWASP Mobile Application Security Project.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] A **mobile operating system** is an operating system used for smartphones, tablets, smartwatches, smartglasses, or other non-laptop personal mobile computing devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] While computers such as laptops are "mobile", the operating systems used on them are usually not considered mobile, as they were originally designed for desktop computers that historically did not have or need specific *mobile* features.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] This "fine line" distinguishing mobile and other forms has become blurred in recent years, due to the fact that newer devices have become smaller and more mobile, unlike the hardware of the past.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Key factors blurring this line are the introduction of tablet computers, light laptops, and the hybridization of the 2-in-1 PCs.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Mobile operating systems combine features of a desktop computer operating system with other features useful for mobile or handheld use, and usually including a wireless built-in modem and SIM tray for telephone and data connection.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] In 2024, approximately **1.22 billion smartphones were sold globally**, marking a 7% increase over the previous year and a solid rebound after two consecutive years of declines.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Sales in 2012 were 1.56 billion; sales in 2023 were 1.43 billion with 53.32% being Android.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Android alone has more sales than the popular desktop operating system Microsoft Windows, and smartphone use (even without tablets) outnumbers desktop use.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Mobile devices, with mobile communications abilities (for example, smartphones), contain two mobile operating systems.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] The main user-facing software platform is supplemented by a second low-level proprietary real-time operating system which operates the radio and other hardware.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Research has shown that these low-level systems may contain a range of security vulnerabilities permitting malicious base stations to gain high levels of control over the mobile device.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Mobile operating systems have had the most use of any operating system since 2017 (measured by web use).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] These operating systems often run atop baseband or other real-time operating systems that handle hardware aspects of the phone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Android (based on the modified Linux kernel) is a mobile operating system developed by Open Handset Alliance.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] The base system is open-source (and only the kernel copyleft), but the apps and drivers which provide functionality are increasingly becoming closed-source.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Although the Android operating system is free and open-source software, in devices sold, much of the software bundled with it (including Google apps and vendor-installed software) is proprietary software and closed-source.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Android's releases before 2.0 (1.0, 1.5, 1.6) were used exclusively on mobile phones.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Android 2.x releases were mostly used for mobile phones but also some tablets.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Android 3.0 was a tablet-oriented release and does not officially run on mobile phones.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Both phone and tablet compatibility were merged with Android 4.0.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Many OEMs ship their devices with custom skins and numerous forks of Android are available to use as custom ROMs.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Wear OS (also known simply as Wear and formerly Android Wear) is a version of Google's Android operating system designed for smartwatches and other wearables.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] By pairing with mobile phones running Android version 6.0 or newer, or iOS version 10.0 or newer with limited support from Google's pairing application, Wear OS integrates Google Assistant technology and mobile notifications into a smartwatch form factor.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] In May 2021 at Google I/O, Google announced a major update to the platform, internally known as Wear OS 3.0.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It incorporates a new visual design inspired by Android 12, and Fitbit exercise tracking features.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Google also announced a partnership with Samsung Electronics, who is collaborating with Google to unify its Tizen-based smartwatch platform with Wear OS, and has committed to using Wear OS on its future smartwatch products starting with One UI Watch 3.0.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] The underlying codebase was also upgraded to Android 11.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] ChromeOS is an operating system designed by Google that is based on the Linux kernel and uses the Google Chrome web browser as its principal user interface.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] As a result, ChromeOS primarily supports web applications.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Google announced the project in July 2009, conceiving it as an operating system in which both applications and user data reside in the cloud: hence ChromeOS primarily runs web applications.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Due to increase of popularity with 2-in-1 PCs, most recent Chromebooks are introduced with touch screen capability, with Android applications starting to become available for the operating system in 2014.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] And in 2016, access to Android apps in the entire Google Play Store was introduced on supported ChromeOS devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] With the support of Android applications, there are Chromebook devices that are positioned as tablet based instead of notebooks.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] ChromeOS is only available pre-installed on hardware from Google manufacturing partners.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] An open source equivalent, ChromiumOS, can be compiled from downloaded source code.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Early on, Google provided design goals for ChromeOS, but has not otherwise released a technical description.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It is open source with GNU General Public License (GPL) for middleware stack core which comes from MER.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Sailfish due to Jolla's business model and due to alliances with various partners and due to intentional design of OS internals, is capable to adopt in several layers third-party software including Jolla software e.g.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Jolla's UI is proprietary software (closed source), so such components can be proprietary with many kinds of licences.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] However, user can replace them with open source components like e.g.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] After Nokia abandoned in 2011 the MeeGo project, most of the MeeGo team left Nokia, and established Jolla as a company to use MeeGo and Mer business opportunities.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] The MER standard allows it to be launched on any hardware with kernel compatible with MER.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] In 2012, Linux Sailfish OS based on MeeGo and using middleware of MER core stack distribution was launched for public use.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] The first device, the Jolla smartphone, was unveiled on May 20, 2013.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] In 2015, Jolla Tablet was launched and the BRICS countries declared it an officially supported OS there.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Jolla started licensing Sailfish OS 2.0 for third parties.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Some devices sold are updateable to Sailfish 2.0 with no limits.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Nemo Mobile is a community-driven OS, similar to Sailfish but attempting to replace its proprietary components, such as the user interface.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] SteamOS is a Linux distribution developed by Valve.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It incorporates Valve's popular namesake Steam video game storefront and is the primary operating system for Steam Machines and the Steam Deck.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] SteamOS is open source with some closed source components.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] SteamOS was originally built to support streaming of video games from one personal computer to the one running SteamOS within the same network, although the operating system can support standalone systems and was intended to be used as part of Valve's Steam Machine platform.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] SteamOS versions 1.0, released in December 2013, and 2.0 were based on the Debian distribution of Linux with GNOME desktop.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] With SteamOS, Valve encouraged developers to incorporate Linux compatibility into their releases to better support Linux gaming options.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] In February 2022, Valve released the handheld gaming computer Steam Deck running SteamOS 3.0.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] SteamOS 3 is based on the Arch Linux distribution with KDE Plasma 5.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Tizen (based on the Linux kernel) is a mobile operating system hosted by Linux Foundation, together with support from the Tizen Association, guided by a Technical Steering Group composed of Intel and Samsung.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Tizen is an operating system for devices including smartphones, tablets, In-Vehicle Infotainment (IVI) devices, however currently it mainly focuses on wearable and smart TVs.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It is an open source system (however the SDK was closed-source and proprietary) that aims to offer a consistent user experience across devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Tizen's main components are the Linux kernel and the WebKit runtime.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] On May 17, 2013, Tizen released version 2.1, code-named Nectarine.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] While Tizen itself was open source, most of the UX and UI layer that was developed by Samsung was mainly closed-source and proprietary, such as the TouchWiz UI on the Samsung Z's series smartphone and One UI for their Galaxy Watch wearable lines.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Note that some refrigerators use Tizen, even though they are not considered mobile devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It is based on Firefox OS/Boot to Gecko.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Unlike most mobile operating systems which focus on smartphones, KaiOS was developed mainly for feature phones, giving these access to more advanced technologies usually found on smartphones, such as app stores and Wi-Fi/4G capabilities.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It is a mix of closed-source and open-source components.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] FirefoxOS/B2G was released under the permissive MPL 2.0.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It does not redistribute itself under the same license, so KaiOS is now presumably proprietary (but still mostly open-source, publishing its source code).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] KaiOS is not entirely proprietary, as it uses the copyleft GPL Linux kernel also used in Android.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Smart Feature OS is a custom version of KaiOS that was developed and solely used by HMD Global for their KaiOS line of Nokia feature phone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] The main differences between stock KaiOS and Smart Feature OS is the aesthetics such as icons, widgets, a custom Nokia ringtone and notification tone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Fuchsia is a capability-based, real-time operating system (RTOS) currently being developed by Google.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It was first discovered as a mysterious code post on GitHub in August 2016, without any official announcement.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] In contrast to prior Google-developed operating systems such as ChromeOS and Android, which are based on Linux kernels, Fuchsia is based on a new microkernel called "Zircon", derived from "Little Kernel", a small operating system intended for embedded systems.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] This allows it to remove Linux and the copyleft GPL under which the Linux kernel is licensed; Fuchsia is licensed under the permissive BSD 3-clause, Apache 2.0, and MIT licenses.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Upon inspection, media outlets noted that the code post on GitHub suggested Fuchsia's capability to run on universal devices, from embedded systems to smartphones, tablets and personal computers.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] In May 2017, Fuchsia was updated with a user interface, along with a developer writing that the project was not a for experimental, prompting media speculation about Google's intentions with the operating system, including the possibility of it replacing Android.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] LiteOS is a discontinued lightweight open source real-time operating system which is part of Huawei's "1+2+1" Internet of Things solution, which is similar to Google Android Things and Samsung Tizen.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It was released under the permissive BSD 3-clause license.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] LiteOS was used in the Huawei Watch GT series and their sub-brand Honor Magic Watch series.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] OpenHarmony is an open-source version of HarmonyOS developed and donated by Huawei to the OpenAtom Foundation.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It supports devices running a mini system with memory as small as 128 KB, or running a standard system with memory greater than 128 MB.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] The open source HarmonyOS is based on the Huawei LiteOS kernel and Linux kernel for standard systems.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] OpenHarmony LiteOS Cortex-A brings small-sized, low-power, and high-performance experience and builds a unified and open ecosystem for developers.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] In addition, it provides rich kernel mechanisms, more comprehensive Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX), and a unified driver framework, Hardware Driver Foundation (HDF), which offers unified access for device developers and friendly development experience for application developers.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Fedora Mobility is under developing mobile operating system by the Fedora Project that are porting Fedora to run on portable devices such as phones and tablets.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] LuneOS is a modern reimplementation of the Palm/HP webOS interface.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Manjaro ARM is a mobile operating system with Plasma Mobile desktop environment that is running and default operating system on the PinePhone, an ARM-based smartphone released by Pine64.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] A mobile Debian focused for PinePhone and soon Librem.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Plasma Mobile is a Plasma variant for smartphones.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Plasma Mobile runs on Wayland and it is compatible with Ubuntu Touch applications, PureOS applications, and eventually Android applications via KDE's Shashlik project – also sponsored by Blue Systems, or Anbox.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It is entirely open-source and thus does not have a cellular modem, so it must make calls by VOIP, like a pocket computer.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] postmarketOS is based on the Alpine Linux Linux distribution.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It is intended to run on older phone hardware.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] PureOS is a Debian GNU/Linux derivative using only free software meeting the Debian Free Software Guidelines, mainly the copyleft GPL.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] PureOS is endorsed by Free Software Foundation as one of the freedom-respecting operating systems.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It is developed by Purism, and was already in use on Purism's laptops before it was used on the Librem 5 smartphone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Purism, in partnership with GNOME and KDE, aims to separate the CPU from the baseband processor and include hardware kill switches for the phone's Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, camera, microphone, and baseband processor, and provide both GNOME and KDE Plasma Mobile as options for the desktop environment.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Ubuntu Touch is an open-source (GPL) mobile version of the Ubuntu operating system originally developed in 2013 by Canonical Ltd. and continued by the non-profit UBports Foundation in 2017.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Ubuntu Touch can run on a pure GNU/Linux base on phones with the required drivers, such as the Librem 5 and the PinePhone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] To enable hardware that was originally shipped with Android, Ubuntu Touch makes use of the Android Linux kernel, using Android drivers and services via an LXC container, but does not use any of the Java-like code of Android.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] As of February 2022, Ubuntu Touch is available on 78 phones and tablets.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] The UBports Installer serves as an easy-to-use tool to allow inexperienced users to install the operating system on third-party devices without damaging their hardware.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] iOS (formerly named iPhone OS) was created by Apple Inc.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It has the second largest installed base worldwide on smartphones, but the largest profits, due to aggressive price competition between Android-based manufacturers.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It is closed-source and proprietary, and is built on the open source Darwin operating system.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] The iPhone, iPod Touch, iPad, and second and third-generation Apple TV all use iOS, which is derived from macOS.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Native third-party applications were not officially supported until the release of iPhone OS 2.0 on July 11, 2008.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Before this, "jailbreaking" allowed third-party applications to be installed.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] In recent years, the jailbreaking scene has changed drastically due to Apple's continued efforts to secure their operating system and prevent unauthorized modifications.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Currently, jailbreaks of recent iterations of iOS are only semi-untethered, which requires a device to be re-jailbroken at every boot, and exploits for jailbreaks are becoming increasingly hard to find and use.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Currently all iOS devices are developed by Apple and manufactured by Foxconn or another of Apple's partners.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] iPadOS is a tablet operating system created and developed by Apple Inc. specifically for their iPad line of tablet computers.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It was announced at the company's 2019 Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC), as a derivation from iOS but with a greater emphasis put on multitasking.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] watchOS is the operating system of the Apple Watch, developed by Apple Inc.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It is based on the iOS operating system and has many similar features.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It was released on April 24, 2015, along with the Apple Watch, the only device that runs watchOS.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It is currently the most widely used wearable operating system.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It features focus on convenience, such as being able to place phone calls and send texts, and health, such as fitness and heart rate tracking.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Kindle firmware is a mobile operating system specifically designed for Amazon Kindle e-readers.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It is based on a custom Linux kernel, but it is mostly closed-source and proprietary.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] HarmonyOS is a distributed operating system developed by Huawei that was specifically designed for smartphones, tablets, TVs, smartwatches, smart devices made by Huawei.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It is based on a proprietary multi-kernel and Linux kernel subsystem.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Released officially for smartphones on June 2, 2021, from its initial launch on August 9, 2019, for smart screen TVs.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] On August 4, 2023, Huawei announces its full stack HarmonyOS NEXT for HarmonyOS that will replace the current multi-kernel stack that contains Linux kernel subsystem with APK apps, with only native HarmonyOS apps able to be used.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] On January 18, 2024, Galaxy Edition version was announced to be used for the next version of HarmonyOS.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] The Nintendo Switch system software (also known by its codename Horizon) is an updatable firmware and operating system used by the Nintendo Switch hybrid video game console/tablet and Nintendo Switch Lite handheld game console.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It is based on a proprietary microkernel.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] The UI includes a HOME screen, consisting of the top bar, the screenshot viewer ("Album"), and shortcuts to the Nintendo eShop, News, and Settings.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] The system itself is based on the Nintendo 3DS system software, additionally the networking stack in the Switch OS is derived at least in part from FreeBSD code while the Stagefright multimedia framework is derived from Android code.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] The PlayStation Vita system software is the official firmware and operating system for the PlayStation Vita and PlayStation TV video game consoles.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It uses the LiveArea as its graphical shell.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] The PlayStation Vita system software has one optional add-on component, the PlayStation Mobile Runtime Package.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] The system is built on a Unix-base which is derived from FreeBSD and NetBSD.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Windows is a personal computer operating system developed and released by Microsoft as part of the Windows NT family of operating systems.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It was released on November 20, 1985, but began focusing on tablet with the release of Windows 8 on October 12, 2012, after earlier attempts with editions based on Windows XP.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] It was designed to run across multiple Microsoft product such as PCs and tablets.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] The Windows user interface was revamped with Windows 8 to provide an improved tablet experience over the interface of Windows 7, including the introduction of modern Windows apps.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Windows 10 would later combine the interface to provide a better experience for mouse-oriented devices and a touchscreen devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Windows 10 also introduced the Universap Windows Platform, these apps can be designed to run across multiple Microsoft product families with nearly identical code‍ including PCs, tablets, smartphones, embedded systems, Xbox One, Surface Hub and Mixed Reality.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Operating System that is primarily designed for their Bip series, however, Huami is currently developing the operating system to run on other smartwatches as well.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Proprietary OS developed by Lenovo for their fitness trackers and smartwatches.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] A proprietary operating system design to run on realme smartbands and smartwatches.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] A proprietary RTOS powering TCL and Alcatel branded smartbands and smartwatches.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p01] Proprietary RTOS that is developed by Huami for the Xiaomi Mi Band series.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] CyanogenMod was a custom mobile operating system based on the Android Open Source Project (AOSP).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] It was a custom ROM that was co-developed by the CyanogenMod community.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] The OS did not include any proprietary apps unless the user installed them.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Due to its open source nature, CyanogenMod allowed Android users who could no longer obtain update support from their manufacturer to continue updating their OS version to the latest one based on official releases from Google AOSP and heavy theme customization.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] The last version of the OS was CyanogenMod 13 which was based on Android Asus.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] On December 24, 2016, CyanogenMod announced on their blog that they would no longer be releasing any CyanogenMod updates.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Cyanogen OS was based on CyanogenMod and maintained by Cyanogen Inc; however, it included proprietary apps and it was only available for commercial uses.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Firefox OS (formerly known as "Boot to Gecko" and shortly "B2G") is from Mozilla.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] It was an open source mobile operating system released under the Mozilla Public License built on the Android Linux kernel and used Android drivers, but did not use any Java-like code of Android.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] MeeGo was from non-profit organization The Linux Foundation.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] At the 2010 Mobile World Congress in Barcelona, Nokia and Intel both unveiled *MeeGo*, a mobile operating system that combined Moblin and Maemo to create an open-sourced experience for users across all devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] In 2011 Nokia announced that it would no longer pursue MeeGo in favor of Windows Phone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Nokia announced the Nokia N9 on June 21, 2011, at the Nokia Connection event in Singapore.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] LG announced its support for the platform.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Maemo was a platform developed by Nokia for smartphones and Internet tablets.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] It is open source and GPL, based on Debian GNU/Linux and draws much of its graphical user interface (GUI), frameworks, and libraries from the GNOME project.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] It uses the Matchbox window manager and the GTK-based Hildon as its GUI and application framework.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] webOS was developed by Palm. webOS is an open source mobile operating system running on the Linux kernel, initially developed by Palm, which launched with the Palm Pre.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] After being acquired by HP, two phones (the Veer and the Pre 3) and a tablet (the TouchPad) running webOS were introduced in 2011.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] On August 18, 2011, HP announced that webOS hardware would be discontinued, but would continue to support and update webOS software and develop the webOS ecosystem.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] HP released webOS as open source under the name Open webOS, and plans to update it with additional features.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] On February 25, 2013, HP announced the sale of webOS to LG Electronics, who used the operating system for its "smart" or Internet-connected TVs.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] However, HP retained patents underlying WebOS and cloud-based services such as the App Catalog.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Bada platform (stylized as bada; Korean: 바다) was an operating system for mobile devices such as smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] It was developed by Samsung Electronics.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Its name is derived from "바다 (bada)", meaning "ocean" or "sea" in Korean.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] It ranges from mid- to high-end smartphones.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] To foster adoption of Bada OS, since 2011 Samsung reportedly has considered releasing the source code under an open-source license, and expanding device support to include Smart TVs.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Samsung announced in June 2012 intentions to merge Bada into the Tizen project, but would meanwhile use its own Bada operating system, in parallel with Google Android OS and Microsoft Windows Phone, for its smartphones.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] All Bada-powered devices are branded under the Wave name, but not all of Samsung's Android-powered devices are branded under the name Galaxy.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] On February 25, 2013, Samsung announced that it will stop developing Bada, moving development to Tizen instead.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Bug reporting was finally terminated in April 2014.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] In 1999, Research In Motion released its first BlackBerry devices, providing secure real-time push-email communications on wireless devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Services such as BlackBerry Messenger provide the integration of all communications into a single inbox.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] In September 2012, RIM announced that the 200 millionth BlackBerry smartphone was shipped.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] As of September 2014, there were around 46 million active BlackBerry service subscribers.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] In the early 2010s, RIM underwent a platform transition, changing its company name to BlackBerry Limited and making new devices using a new operating system named "BlackBerry 10".
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] BlackBerry 10 (based on the QNX OS) is from BlackBerry.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] As a smartphone OS, it is closed-source and proprietary, and only runs on phones and tablets manufactured by BlackBerry.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] One of the dominant platforms in the world in the late 2000s, its global market share was reduced significantly by the mid-2010s.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] In late 2016, BlackBerry announced that it will continue to support the OS, with a promise to release 10.3.3.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Therefore, BlackBerry 10 would not receive any major updates as BlackBerry and its partners would focus more on their Android base development.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] The Nintendo 3DS system software is the updatable operating system used by the Nintendo 3DS.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Symbian platform was developed by Nokia for some models of smartphones.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] It is proprietary software, it was however used by Ericsson (Sony Ericsson), Sending and Benq.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] The operating system was discontinued in 2012, although a slimmed-down version for basic phones was still developed until July 2014.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Microsoft officially shelved the platform in favor of Windows Phone after its acquisition of Nokia.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] It is closed-source and proprietary. webOS was introduced by Palm in January 2009, as the successor to Palm OS with Web 2.0 technologies, open architecture and multitasking abilities.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Windows Mobile was a family of proprietary operating systems from Microsoft aimed at business and enterprise users, based on Windows CE and originally developed for Pocket PC (PDA) devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] In 2010 it was replaced with the consumer-focused Windows Phone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Versions of Windows Mobile came in multiple editions, like "Pocket PC Premium", "Pocket PC Professional", "Pocket PC Phone", and "Smartphone" (Windows Mobile 2003) or "Professional", "Standard", and "Classic" (Windows Mobile 6.0).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Some editions were touchscreen-only and some were keyboard-only, although there were cases where device vendors managed to graft support for one onto an edition targeted at the other.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Cellular phone features were also only supported by some editions.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Microsoft started work on a version of Windows Mobile that would combine all features together, but it was aborted, and instead they focused on developing the non-backward-compatible, touchscreen-only Windows Phone 7.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Windows Phone is a proprietary mobile operating system developed by Microsoft for smartphones as the replacement successor to Windows Mobile and Zune.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Windows Phone features a new touchscreen-oriented user interface derived from Metro design language.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Unveiled on February 15, 2010, Windows Phone included a user interface inspired by Microsoft's Metro Design Language.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] It was integrated with Microsoft services such as OneDrive and Office, Xbox Music, Xbox Video, Xbox Live games, and Bing, but also integrated with many other non-Microsoft services such as Facebook and Google accounts.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Windows Phone devices were made primarily by Microsoft Mobile/Nokia, and also by HTC and Samsung.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] On January 21, 2015, Microsoft announced that the Windows Phone brand would be phased out and replaced with Windows 10 Mobile, bringing tighter integration and unification with its PC counterpart Windows 10, and providing a platform for smartphones and tablets with screen sizes under 8 inches.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] On October 8, 2017, Microsoft officially announced that they would no longer push any major updates to Windows 10 Mobile.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] The operating system was put in maintenance mode, where Microsoft would push bug fixes and general improvements only.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Windows 10 Mobile would not receive any new feature updates.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] On January 18, 2019, Microsoft announced that support for Windows 10 Mobile would end on December 10, 2019, with no further security updates released after then, and that Windows 10 Mobile users should migrate to iOS or Android phones.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] In 1992, the first smartphone prototype, the IBM Simon, was first showcased.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] The IBM Simon, was released commercially in 1994.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] It ran on the Datalight ROM-DOS operating system.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Between 1999 and 2002, Palm OS was the dominant player in the market, reaching 74% market share in 2000.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Symbian overtook Palm OS as the leading player in 2003.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] And starting losing shares thereafter but remained the largest player until 2012.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] In 2006, Android and iOS did not exist and only 64 million smartphones were sold.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] In 2018 Q1, 183.5 million smartphones were sold and global market share was 48.9% for Android and 19.1% for iOS.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Only 131,000 smartphones running other operating systems were sold, constituting 0.03% of sales.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] According to StatCounter web use statistics (a proxy for all use), smartphones (alone without tablets) have majority use globally, with desktop computers used much less (and Android, in particular, more popular than Windows).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Use varies however by continent with smartphones way more popular in the biggest continents, i.e.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Asia, and the desktop still more popular in some, though not in North America.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] The desktop is still popular in many countries (while overall down to 44.9% in the first quarter of 2017), smartphones are more popular even in many developed countries (or about to be in more).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] A few countries on any continent are desktop-minority; European countries (and some in South America, and a few, e.g.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Haiti, in North America; and most in Asia and Africa) are smartphone-majority, Poland and Turkey highest with 57.68% and 62.33%, respectively.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] In Ireland, smartphone use at 45.55% outnumbers desktop use and mobile as a whole gains majority when including the tablet share at 9.12%.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Spain is also slightly desktop-minority.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Smartphones (alone, without tablets), first gained majority in December 2016 (desktop-majority was lost the month before), and it was not a Christmas-time fluke, as while close to majority after smartphone majority happened again in March 2017.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] In the week from November 7–13, 2016, smartphones alone (without tablets) overtook desktop, for the first time (for a short period; non-full-month).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Mobile-majority applies to countries such as Paraguay in South America, Poland in Europe and Turkey; and most of Asia and Africa.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Some of the world is still desktop-majority, with e.g. in the United States at 54.89% (but no not on all days).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] However, in some territories of the United States, such as Puerto Rico, desktop is way under majority, with Windows under 30% overtaken by Android.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] On October 22, 2016 (and subsequent weekends), mobile showed majority.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Since October 27, the desktop has not shown majority, not even on weekdays.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Smartphones alone have shown majority since December 23 to the end of the year, with the share topping at 58.22% on Christmas Day.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] To the "mobile"-majority share then of smartphones, tablets could be added giving a 63.22% majority.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] While an unusually high top, a similarly high also happened on Monday April 17, 2017, with then only smartphones share slightly lower and tablet share slightly higher, with them combined at 62.88%.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] According to a StatCounter November 1, 2016 press release, the world has turned desktop-minority; at about 49% desktop use for the previous month, but mobile was not ranked higher, tablet share had to be added to it to exceed desktop share.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] By now, mobile (smartphones) have full majority, outnumbering desktop/laptop computers by a safe margin (and no longer counting tablets with desktops makes them most popular).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Samsung released its last Tizen powered smartphone in 2017.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Tizen peaked in that March at 0.25% market share.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Firefox OS and Tizen both peaked in monthly market share in 2018 at 0.51% and 1.13% respectively.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Between 2018 and 2021, iOS and Android formed a mobile operating system duopoly, with no other OS reaching more than 1% market share for the full year.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Microsoft ended support for its final mobile OS, Windows 10 Mobile, in January 2020.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic led to a significant reduction in smartphone sales in 2020, with a 12.5% sales diminution year over year.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] 2021 marked the apex of Android market share.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] In February 2023, IIT Madras released BharOS, a GrapheneOS fork.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Since release, BharOS has had a 0% market share.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Huawei announced HarmonyOS Next in August 2023.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] This was the first iteration of Harmony OS to not include the AOSP core.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Harmony OS's market share prior to release was 2%.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] As of quarter 1 of 2025, Android was still by far the largest player with over three quarters, or 76%, of the market share. iOS remained solidly second with 19% of sales.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] This was the first mobile OS to reach the 5% milestone besides Android and iOS since Symbian 10 years prior.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-operating-system-p02] Other includes all other smartphone OSes but not feature phone OSes.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Increasingly, users and businesses use smartphones not only to communicate, but also to plan and organize their work and private life.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Within companies, these technologies are causing profound changes in the organization of information systems and have therefore become the source of new risks.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Indeed, smartphones collect and compile an increasing amount of sensitive information to which access must be controlled to protect the privacy of the user and the intellectual property of the company.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The majority of attacks are aimed at smartphones.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Smartphone operating systems or browsers are another weakness.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Some malware makes use of the common user's limited knowledge.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Only 2.1% of users reported having first-hand contact with mobile malware, according to a 2008 McAfee study, which found that 11.6% of users had heard of someone else being harmed by the problem.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Yet, it is predicted that this number will rise.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] As of December 2023, there were about 5.4 million global mobile cyberattacks per month.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] This is a 147% increase from the previous year.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Security countermeasures are being developed and applied to smartphones, from security best practices in software to the dissemination of information to end users.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Countermeasures can be implemented at all levels, including operating system development, software design, and user behavior modifications.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] A smartphone user is exposed to various threats when they use their phone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] In just the last two quarters of 2012, the number of unique mobile threats grew by 261%, according to ABI Research.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] These threats can disrupt the operation of the smartphone and transmit or modify user data.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Applications must guarantee privacy and integrity of the information they handle.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Malicious apps can also be installed without the owners' permission or knowledge.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Vulnerability in mobile devices refers to aspects of system security that are susceptible to attacks.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] A vulnerability occurs when there is system weakness, an attacker has access to the weakness, and the attacker has competency to exploit the weakness.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Potential attackers began looking for vulnerabilities when Apple's iPhone and the first Android devices came onto the market.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Since the introduction of apps (particularly mobile banking apps), which are vital targets for hackers, malware has been rampant.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The Department of Homeland Security's cybersecurity department claims that the number of vulnerable points in smartphone operating systems has increased.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] As mobile phones are connected to utilities and appliances, hackers, cybercriminals, and even intelligence officials have access to these devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Starting in 2011, it became increasingly popular to let employees use their own devices for work-related purposes.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The Crowd Research Partners study, published in 2017, reports that during 2017, most businesses that mandated the use of mobile devices were subjected to malware attacks and breaches.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] It has become common for rogue applications to be installed on user devices without the user's permission.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] They breach privacy, which hinders the effectiveness of the devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Since the recent rise of mobile attacks, hackers have increasingly targeted smartphones through credential theft and snooping.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The number of attacks targeting smartphones and other devices has risen by 50 percent.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] According to the study, mobile banking applications are responsible for the increase in attacks.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Malware—such as ransomware, worms, botnets, Trojans, and viruses—have been developed to exploit vulnerabilities in mobile devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Malware is distributed by attackers so they can gain access to private information or digitally harm a user.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] For example, should malware breach a user's banking service, it may be able to access their transaction information, their rights to log in, and their money.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Some malware is developed with anti-detection techniques to avoid detection.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Attackers who use malware can avoid detection by hiding malicious code.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Trojan-droppers can also avoid detection of malware.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Despite the fact that the malware inside a device does not change, the dropper generates new hashes each time.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Additionally, droppers can also create a multitude of files, which can lead to the creation of viruses.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Android mobile devices are prone to Trojan-droppers.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The banking Trojans also enable attacks on the banking applications on the phone, which leads to the theft of data for use in stealing money and funds.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Jailbreaks for iOS devices work by disabling the signing of codes on iPhones so that applications not downloaded from the App Store can be operated.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] In this way, all the protection layers offered by iOS are disrupted, exposing the device to malware.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] These outside applications don't run in a sandbox, which exposes potential security problems.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Some attack vectors change the mobile devices' configuration settings by installing malicious credentials and virtual private networks (VPNs) to direct information to malicious systems.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] In addition, spyware can be installed on mobile devices in order to track an individual.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Triade malware comes pre-installed on some mobile devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] In addition to Haddad, there is Lotoor, which exploits vulnerabilities in the system to repackage legitimate applications.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The devices are also vulnerable due to spyware and leaky behaviors through applications.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Mobile devices are also effective conveyance systems for malware threats, breaches of information, and thefts.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Wi-Fi interference technologies can also attack mobile devices through potentially insecure networks.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] By compromising the network, hackers are able to gain access to key data.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Devices connected to public networks are at risk of attacks.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] A VPN, on the other hand, can be used to secure networks.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] As soon as a system is threatened, an active VPN will operate.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] There are also social engineering techniques, such as phishing, in which unsuspecting victims are sent links to lead them to malicious websites.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The attackers can then hack into the victim's device and copy all of its information.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Some mobile device attacks can be prevented.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] For example, containerization allows the creation of a hardware infrastructure that separates business data from other data.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Additionally, network protection detects malicious traffic and rogue access points.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Data security is also ensured through authentication.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] There are a number of threats to mobile devices, including annoyance, stealing money, invading privacy, propagation, and malicious tools.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Identity – Smartphones are highly customizable, so the device or its contents can easily be associated with a specific person.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Availability – Attacking a smartphone can limit or deprive a user's access to it.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Some attacks derive from flaws in the management of Short Message Service (SMS) and Multimedia Messaging Service (MMS).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Some mobile phone models have problems in managing binary SMS messages.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] By sending an ill-formed block, it is possible to cause the phone to restart, leading to the denial-of-service attacks.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] If a user with a Siemens S55 received a text message containing a Chinese character, it would lead to a denial of service.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] This attack is called "curse of silence".
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] A study on the safety of the SMS infrastructure revealed that SMS messages sent from the Internet can be used to perform a distributed denial of service (DDoS) attack against the mobile telecommunications infrastructure of a big city.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The attack exploits the delays in the delivery of messages to overload the network.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Another potential attack could begin with a phone that sends an MMS to other phones, with an attachment.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] This attachment is infected with a virus.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Upon receipt of the MMS, the user can choose to open the attachment.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] If it is opened, the phone is infected, and the virus sends an MMS with an infected attachment to all the contacts in the address book.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] There is a real-world example of this attack: the virus Commwarrior sends MMS messages (including an infected file) to all recipients in a mobile phone's address book.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] If a recipient installs the infected file, the virus repeats, sending messages to recipients taken from the new address book.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The attacker may try to break the encryption of a GSM mobile network.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The network encryption algorithms belong to the family of algorithms called A5.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Due to the policy of security through obscurity, it has not been possible to openly test the robustness of these algorithms.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] There were originally two variants of the algorithm: A5/1 and A5/2 (stream ciphers), where the former was designed to be relatively strong, and the latter was purposely designed to be weak to allow easy cryptanalysis and eavesdropping.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] ETSI forced some countries (typically outside Europe) to use A5/2.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Since the encryption algorithm was made public, it was proved to be breakable: A5/2 could be broken on the fly, and A5/1 in about 6 hours.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] In July 2007, the 3GPP approved a change request to prohibit the implementation of A5/2 in any new mobile phones, decommissioning the algorithm; it is no longer implemented in mobile phones.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Stronger public algorithms have been added to the GSM standard: the A5/3 and A5/4 (Block ciphers), otherwise known as KASUMI or UEA1 published by ETSI.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] If the network does not support A5/1, or any other A5 algorithm implemented by the phone, then the base station can specify A5/0 which is the null algorithm, whereby the radio traffic is sent unencrypted.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Even if mobile phones are able to use 3G or 4G (which have much stronger encryption than 2G GSM), the base station can downgrade the radio communication to 2G GSM and specify A5/0 (no encryption).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] This is the basis for eavesdropping attacks on mobile radio networks using a fake base station commonly called an IMSI catcher.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] In addition, tracing of mobile terminals is difficult since each time the mobile terminal is accessing or being accessed by the network, a new temporary identity (TMSI) is allocated to the mobile terminal.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The TMSI is used as the identity of the mobile terminal the next time it accesses the network.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The TMSI is sent to the mobile terminal in encrypted messages.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Once the encryption algorithm of GSM is broken, the attacker can intercept all unencrypted communications made by the victim's smartphone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] An attacker can try to eavesdrop on Wi-Fi communications to derive information (e.g., username, password).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] This type of attack is not unique to smartphones, but they are very vulnerable to these attacks because often Wi-Fi is their only means of communication and access the internet.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The security of wireless networks (WLAN) is thus an important subject.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Initially, wireless networks were secured by WEP keys.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The weakness of WEP is its short encryption key, which is the same for all connected clients.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] In addition, several reductions in the search space of the keys have been found by researchers.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Now, most wireless networks are protected by the WPA security protocol.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] WPA is based on the Temporal Key Integrity Protocol (TKIP), which was designed to allow migration from WEP to WPA on the equipment already deployed.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The major improvements in security are the dynamic encryption keys.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] For small networks, the WPA uses a "pre-shared key" which is based on a shared key.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Encryption can be vulnerable if the length of the shared key is short.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] With limited opportunities for input (i.e., only the numeric keypad), mobile phone users might define short encryption keys that contain only numbers.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] This increases the likelihood that an attacker succeeds with a brute-force attack.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The successor to WPA, called WPA2, is supposed to be safe enough to withstand a brute force attack.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The ability to access free and fast Wi-Fi gives a business an edge over those who do not.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Free Wi-Fi is usually provided by organizations such as airports, coffee shops, and restaurants for a number of reasons, including encouraging customers to spend more time and money on the premises, and helping users stay productive.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Another reason is enhancing customer tracking: many restaurants and coffee shops compile data about their customers so they can target advertisements directly to their devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] This means that customers know what services the facility provides.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Generally, individuals filter business premises based on Internet connections as another reason to gain a competitive edge.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Network security is the responsibility of the organizations, as unsecured Wi-Fi networks are prone to numerous risks.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The man-in-the-middle attack entails the interception and modification of data between parties.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Additionally, malware can be distributed via the free Wi-Fi network and hackers can exploit software vulnerabilities to smuggle malware onto connected devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] It is also possible to eavesdrop and sniff Wi-Fi signals using special software and devices, capturing login credentials and hijacking accounts.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] As with GSM, if the attacker succeeds in breaking the identification key, both the phone and the entire network it is connected to become exposed to attacks.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Many smartphones remember wireless LANs they have previously connected to, allowing users to not have to re-identify with each connection.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] However, an attacker could create a Wi-Fi access point twin with the same parameters and characteristics as a real network.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] By automatically connecting to the fraudulent network, a smartphone becomes susceptible to the attacker, who can intercept any unencrypted data.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Lasco is a worm that initially infects a remote device using the SIS file format, a type of script file that can be executed by the system without user interaction.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The smartphone thus believes the file to come from a trusted source and downloads it, infecting the machine.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Security issues related to Bluetooth on mobile devices have been studied and have shown numerous problems on different phones.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] One easy to exploit vulnerability is that unregistered services do not require authentication, and vulnerable applications have a virtual serial port used to control the phone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] An attacker only needed to connect to the port to take full control of the device.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] In another example, an attacker sends a file via Bluetooth to a phone within range with Bluetooth in discovery mode.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] If the recipient accepts, a virus is transmitted.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] An example of this is a worm called Cabir.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The worm searches for nearby phones with Bluetooth in discoverable mode and sends itself to the target device.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The user must accept the incoming file and install the program, after which the worm infects the machine.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Other attacks are based on flaws in the OS or applications on the phone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The mobile web browser is an emerging attack vector for mobile devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Just as common Web browsers, mobile web browsers are extended from pure web navigation with widgets and plug-ins or are completely native mobile browsers.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Jailbreaking the iPhone with firmware 1.1.1 was based entirely on vulnerabilities on the web browser.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] In this case, there was a vulnerability based on a stack-based buffer overflow in a library used by the web browser (LibTIFF).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] A similar vulnerability in the web browser for Android was discovered in October 2008.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Like the iPhone vulnerability, it was due to an obsolete and vulnerable library, but significantly differed in that Android's sandboxing architecture limited the effects of this vulnerability to the Web browser process.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Smartphones are also susceptible to traditional forms of web-based attacks, including phishing, malicious websites, and background-running malware.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Unlike computers, however, robust antivirus solutions for smartphones are not yet widely available.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Industry mobile security research also highlights rising risks from application reverse engineering, runtime tampering, and API exploitation in mobile apps.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The Internet offers numerous interactive features that ensure a higher engagement rate, capture more and relevant data, and increase brand loyalty.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Blogs, forums, social networks, and wikis are some of the most common interactive websites.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Due to the tremendous growth of the Internet, there has been a rapid rise in the number of security breaches experienced by individuals and businesses.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Mobile browser users can balance usage and caution in several ways, such as reviewing computer security regularly, using secure and secret passwords, and correcting, upgrading, and replacing the necessary features.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Installation of antivirus and anti-spyware programs is the most effective way of protecting the computer, as they offer protection against malware, spyware, and viruses.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Additionally, they use firewalls, which are typically installed between trusted networks or devices and the Internet.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] By acting as a web server, the firewall prevents external users from accessing the internal computer system.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Sometimes it is possible to overcome the security safeguards by modifying the operating system (OS) itself, such as the manipulation of firmware and malicious signature certificates.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] In 2004, vulnerabilities in virtual machines running on certain devices were revealed.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] It was possible to bypass the bytecode verifier and access the native underlying operating system.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The results of this research were not published in detail.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The firmware security of Nokia's Symbian Platform Security Architecture (PSA) is based on a central configuration file called SWIPolicy.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] In 2008, it was possible to manipulate the Nokia firmware before it was installed.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] In fact, some downloadable versions of this file were human-readable, so it was possible to modify and change the image of the firmware.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] This vulnerability was solved by an update from Nokia.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] In theory, smartphones have an advantage over hard drives since the OS files are in read-only memory (ROM) and cannot be changed by malware.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] However, in some systems it was possible to circumvent this: in the Symbian OS, it was possible to overwrite a file with a file of the same name.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] On the Windows OS, it was possible to change a pointer from a general configuration file to an editable file.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] When an application is installed, the signing of this application is verified by a series of certificates.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] One can create a valid signature without using a valid certificate and add it to the list.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] In the Symbian OS, all certificates are in the directory `c:\resource\swicertstore\dat`.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] With firmware changes explained above, it is very easy to insert a seemingly valid but malicious certificate.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Android is the OS that has been attacked the most, because it has the largest userbase.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] A cybersecurity company reported to have blocked about 18 million attacks in 2016.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] In 2015, researchers at the French government agency *Agence nationale de la sécurité des systèmes d'information* (ANSSI, lit.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] 'French National Agency for the Security of Information Systems') demonstrated the capability to trigger the voice interface of certain smartphones remotely by using "specific electromagnetic waveforms".
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The exploit took advantage of antenna-properties of headphone wires while plugged into the audio-output jacks of the vulnerable smartphones and effectively spoofed audio input to inject commands via the audio interface.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Juice jacking is a physical or hardware vulnerability specific to mobile platforms.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Utilizing the dual purpose of the USB charge port, many devices have been susceptible to having data exfiltrated from, or malware installed onto, a mobile device by utilizing malicious charging kiosks set up in public places or hidden in normal charge adapters.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Jailbreaking is also a physical access vulnerability, in which a mobile device user hacks into device to unlock it, exploiting weaknesses in the operating system.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Mobile device users take control of their own device by jailbreaking it, allowing them to customize the interface by installing applications, change system settings that are not allowed on the devices, tweak OS processes, and run uncertified programs.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] This openness exposes the device to a variety of malicious attacks which can compromise private data.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] In 2010, researchers from the University of Pennsylvania investigated the possibility of cracking a device's password through a smudge attack (literally imaging the finger smudges on the screen to discern the user's password).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] The researchers were able to discern the device password up to 68% of the time under certain conditions.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p01] Outsiders may perform over-the-shoulder surveillance on victims, such as watching specific keystrokes or pattern gestures, to unlock device password or passcode.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] As smartphones are a permanent point of access to the Internet (they are often turned on), they can be compromised with malware as easily as computers.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] A malware is a computer program that aims to harm the system in which it resides.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Trojans, worms and viruses are all considered malware.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] A Trojan is a program on a device that allows external users to connect discreetly.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] A worm is a program that reproduces on multiple computers across a network.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] A virus is a malicious software designed to spread to other computers by inserting itself into legitimate programs and running programs in parallel.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Malware is far less numerous and serious to smartphones as it is to computers.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Nonetheless, recent studies show that the evolution of malware in smartphones have rocketed in the last few years posing a threat to analysis and detection.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] In 2017, mobile malware variants increased by 54%.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Various common apps installed by millions can intrude on privacy, even if they were installed from a trusted software distribution service like the Google Play Store.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] For example, in 2022 it was shown that the popular app TikTok collects a lot of data and is required to make it available to the Chinese Communist Party (CCP) due to a national security law.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This includes personal information on millions of Americans.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] The firmware and "stock software" preinstalled on devices – and updated with preinstalled software – can also have undesired components or privacy-intruding default configurations or substantial security vulnerabilities.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] In 2019, Kryptowire identified Android devices with malicious firmware that collected and transmitted sensitive data without users' consent.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Analysis of data traffic by popular smartphones running variants of Android found substantial by-default data collection and sharing with no opt-out by pre-installed software.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This issue also can't be addressed by conventional security patches.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Outgoing Internet traffic can be analyzed with packet analyzers and with firewall apps like the NetGuard firewall app for Android that allows reading blocked traffic logs.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Typically, an attack on a smartphone made by malware takes place in three phases: the infection of a host, the accomplishment of its goal, and the spread of the malware to other systems.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Malware often uses the resources offered by infected smartphones.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] It will use the output devices such as Bluetooth or infrared, but it may also use the address book or email address of the person to infect the user's acquaintances.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] The malware exploits the trust that is given to data sent by an acquaintance.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Infection is the method used by malware to gain access to the smartphone; it may exploit an internal vulnerability or rely on the gullibility of the user.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Implied permission – This infection is based on the fact that the user has a habit of installing software.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Most Trojans try to seduce the user into installing attractive applications (like games or useful applications) that actually contain malware.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Common interaction – This infection is related to a common behavior, such as opening an MMS or email.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] No interaction – The device is infected without the user taking action.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This class of infection is the most dangerous, as it is both unapproved and automatic.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Once the malware has infected a smartphone, it aims to spread to a new host.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This usually occurs to proximate devices via Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, or infrared; or to remote networks via telephone calls, SMS, or emails.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Mobile ransomware is a type of malware that locks users out of their mobile devices in a pay-to-unlock-your-device ploy.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] It has significantly grown as a threat category since 2014.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Mobile users are often less security-conscious – particularly as it pertains to scrutinizing applications and web links – and trust the mobile device's native protection capability.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Mobile ransomware poses a significant threat to businesses reliant on instant access and availability of their proprietary information and contacts.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] The likelihood of a traveling businessman paying a ransom to unlock their device is significantly higher since they are at a disadvantage given inconveniences such as timeliness and less direct access to IT staff.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Recent ransomware attacks have caused many Internet-connected devices to not work and are costly for companies to recover from.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Attackers can make their malware target multiple platforms.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Some malware attacks operating systems but is able to spread across different systems.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] To begin with, malware can use runtime environments like Java virtual machine or the .NET Framework.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] They can also use other libraries present in many operating systems.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Some malware carries several executable files in order to run in multiple environments, utilizing these during the propagation process.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] In practice, this type of malware requires a connection between the two operating systems to use as an attack vector.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Memory cards can be used for this purpose, or synchronization software can be used to propagate the virus.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Mobile security is divided into different categories, as methods do not all act at the same level and are designed to prevent different threats.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] These methods range from the management of security by the operating system (protecting the system from corruption by an application) to the behavioral education of the user (preventing the installation of a suspicious software).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Among the mechanisms that handle device-access protection, some services or third-party tools can assist in unlocking or resetting locked devices after a factory reset or FRP (Factory Reset Protection).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] The first layer of security in a smartphone is the operating system.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Beyond needing to handle the usual roles (e.g., resource management, scheduling processes) on the device, it must also establish the protocols for introducing external applications and data without introducing risk.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] A central paradigm in mobile operating systems is the idea of a sandbox.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Since smartphones are currently designed to accommodate many applications, they must have mechanisms to ensure these applications are safe for the phone itself, for other applications and data on the system, and for the user.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] If a malicious program reaches a mobile device, the vulnerable area presented by the system must be as small as possible.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Sandboxing extends this idea to compartmentalize different processes, preventing them from interacting and damaging each other.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Based on the history of operating systems, sandboxing has different implementations.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] For example, where iOS will focus on limiting access to its public API for applications from the App Store by default, Managed Open In allows you to restrict which apps can access which types of data.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Android bases its sandboxing on its legacy of Linux and TrustedBSD.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] The following points highlight mechanisms implemented in operating systems, especially Android.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] in the system is a great danger in the same way as on a computer.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] It is important to prevent such intrusions, and to be able to detect them as often as possible.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Indeed, there is concern that with this type of malicious program, an attacker could partially or completely bypass the device security, or acquire administrator rights.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] If this happens, nothing prevents the attacker from studying or disabling the safety features that were circumvented, deploying the applications they want, or disseminating a method of intrusion by a rootkit to a wider audience.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This mechanism relies on signatures from applications required to start the operating system, and a certificate signed by the manufacturer (Apple).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] In the event that the signature checks are inconclusive, the device detects this and stops the boot-up.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] If the operating system is compromised due to jailbreaking, rootkit detection may not work if it is disabled by the jailbreak method or software is loaded after jailbreak disables Rootkit Detection.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Android uses mechanisms of user process isolation inherited from Linux.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This approach serves as a sandbox: while applications can be malicious, they cannot get out of the sandbox reserved for them by their identifiers, and thus cannot interfere with the proper functioning of the system.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] For example, since it is impossible for a process to end the process of another user, an application can thus not stop the execution of another application.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Permissions prevent a process from editing any files it wants.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] It is therefore not possible to freely corrupt files necessary for the operation of another application or system.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Furthermore, in Android there is the method of locking memory permissions.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] It is not possible to change the permissions of files installed on the SD card from the phone, and consequently it is impossible to install applications.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This could occur if a process managed to reach an area allocated to other processes, where it could write in the memory of a process with rights superior to its own (with 'root' in the worst case) and perform actions beyond its permissions.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] It would suffice to insert function calls are authorized by the privileges of the malicious application.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Software is often developed in high-level languages, which can control what is being done by a running program.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] continuously monitor the actions of the execution threads they manage, monitor and assign resources, and prevent malicious actions.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Buffer overflows can be prevented by these controls.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Above the operating system security, there is a layer of security software.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This layer is composed of individual components to strengthen various vulnerabilities: prevent malware, intrusions, the identification of a user as a human, and user authentication.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] It contains software components that have learned from their experience with computer security; however, on smartphones, this software must deal with greater constraints (see limitations).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] An antivirus software can be deployed on a device to verify that it is not infected by a known threat, usually by signature detection software that detects malicious executable files.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] A mobile antivirus product would scan files and compare them against a database of known mobile malware code signatures.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] A firewall, meanwhile, can watch over the existing traffic on the network and ensure that a malicious application does not seek to communicate through it.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] It may equally verify that an installed application does not seek to establish suspicious communication, which may prevent an intrusion attempt.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] In order to make the user aware of any abnormal actions, such as a call they did not initiate, one can link some functions to a visual notification that is impossible to circumvent.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] For example, when a call is triggered, the called number should always be displayed.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Thus, if a call is triggered by a malicious application, the user can see, and take appropriate action.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] It is important to confirm certain actions by a user decision.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] One advantage of using biometric security is that users can avoid having to remember a password or other secret combination to authenticate and prevent malicious users from accessing their devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] In a system with strong biometric security, only the primary user can access the smartphone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Should a malicious application pass the security barriers, it can take the actions for which it was designed.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] However, this activity can be sometimes detected by monitoring the various resources used on the phone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Depending on the goals of the malware, the consequences of infection are not always the same; all malicious applications are not intended to harm the devices on which they are deployed.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] The following resources are only indications and do not provide certainty about the legitimacy of the activity of an application.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] However, these criteria can help target suspicious applications, especially if several criteria are combined.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Some malware is aimed at exhausting the energy resources of the phone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Monitoring the energy consumption of the phone can be a way to detect certain malware applications.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Memory usage is inherent in any application.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] However, if one finds that an unnecessary or unexpected proportion of memory is used by an application, it may be flagged as suspicious.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] As part of normal operation on a smartphone, many applications are bound to connect via the network.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] However, an application using a lot of bandwidth can be strongly suspected of attempting to communicate a lot of information and disseminate data to many other devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] One can monitor the activity of various services of a smartphone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] During certain moments, some services should not be active, and if one is detected, the application should be suspected.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] For example, the sending of an SMS when the user is filming video: this communication does not make sense and is suspicious; malware may attempt to send SMS while its activity is masked.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Network traffic exchanged by phones can be monitored.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] One can place safeguards in network routing points in order to detect abnormal behavior.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] As the mobile's use of network protocols is much more constrained than that of a computer, expected network data streams can be predicted (e.g., the protocol for sending an SMS), which permits detection of anomalies in mobile networks.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] can be detected through means of mobile communications (SMS, MMS).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] It is therefore possible to detect and minimize this kind of attempt by filters deployed on network infrastructure that is relaying these messages.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Because it is always possible that data exchanged can be intercepted, communications and information storage rely on encryption to prevent a malicious entity from using any data obtained during communications.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] However, this poses the problem of key exchange for encryption algorithms, which requires a secure channel.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This implies that one cannot predict the flow of data from common web protocols; a protocol might generate very little traffic by consulting simple pages (rarely) or generate heavy traffic by using video streaming.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] On the other hand, messages exchanged via mobile phone have a framework and a specific model, and the user does not, in a normal case, have the freedom to intervene in the details of these communications.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Therefore, if an abnormality is found in the flux of network data in the mobile networks, the potential threat can be quickly detected.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] In the production and distribution chain for mobile devices, manufacturers are responsibility for ensuring that devices are delivered in a basic configuration without vulnerabilities.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Most users are not experts and many of them are not aware of the existence of security vulnerabilities, so the device configuration as provided by manufacturers will be retained by many users.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Some smartphone manufacturers add Titan M2s (a security hardware chip) to increase mobile security.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Phones are sometimes set in a debug mode during manufacturing, but this mode must be disabled before the phone is sold.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This mode allows access to features not intended for routine use by a user.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Due to the speed of development and production, distractions occur, and some devices are sold in debug mode.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This kind of deployment exposes mobile devices to exploits that utilize this oversight.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] When a smartphone is sold, its default settings must be correct, and not leave security gaps.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] The default configuration is not always changed, so a good initial setup is essential for users.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] There are, for example, default configurations that are vulnerable to denial-of-service attacks.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] App stores have emerged alongside smartphones.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Both users and providers are tasked with examining the immense volume of apps available, from different points of view (e.g., security, content).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Security audits should be particularly cautious, because if a fault is not detected, the application can spread very quickly within a few days, and infect a significant number of devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] When installing applications, it is good to warn the user against sets of permissions that, grouped together, seem potentially dangerous, or at least suspicious.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Frameworks like such as Kirin, on Android, attempt to detect and prohibit certain sets of permissions.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] First developed for Android, a process known as 'remote revocation' can remotely and globally uninstall an application from any device that has it.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This means the spread of a malicious application that evaded security checks can be immediately stopped when the threat is discovered.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Manufacturers are tempted to overlay custom layers on existing operating systems, with the dual purpose of offering customized options and disabling or charging for certain features.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This has the dual effect of risking the introduction of new bugs in the system, coupled with an incentive for users to modify the systems to circumvent the manufacturer's restrictions.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] These systems are rarely as stable and reliable as the original and may suffer from phishing attempts or other exploits.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] New versions of various software components of a smartphone, including operating systems, are regularly published.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] These 'patches' correct flaws over time.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Nevertheless, manufacturers often do not deploy these updates to their devices in a timely fashion, and sometimes not at all.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Thus, vulnerabilities can persist when they could be corrected; while they exist and are generally known, they are easily exploitable.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] The user has a large responsibility in the cycle of security.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This can be as simple as using a password, or as detailed as precisely controlling which permissions are granted to applications.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This precaution is especially important if the user is an employee of a company who stores business data on the device.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Much malicious behavior is allowed by user carelessness.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Smartphone users were found to ignore security messages during application installation, especially during application selection and checking application reputation, reviews, security, and agreement messages.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] A recent survey by internet security experts BullGuard showed a lack of insight concerning the rising number of malicious threats affecting mobile phones, with 53% of users claiming that they are unaware of security software for smartphones.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] A further 21% argued that such protection was unnecessary, and 42% admitted it hadn't crossed their mind ("Using APA," 2011).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] These statistics show that consumers are not concerned about security risks because they believe it is not a serious problem.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] However, in truth, smartphones are effectively handheld computers and are just as vulnerable.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] A user should not believe everything that may be presented, as some information may be wrong, misleading, phishing, or attempting to distribute a malicious application.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] It is therefore advisable to check an application's reputation before buying or installing it.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] The mass distribution of applications necessitates different permissions mechanisms for each operating system.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] It is necessary to clarify these permissions mechanisms to users, as they differ between systems and can be confusing.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] In addition, it is rarely feasible (or possible) to modify large sets of permissions requested by an application.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] However, this can be a source of risk because a user can grant an application excessive rights beyond what is necessary.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] For example, a note-taking application does not require access to the geolocation service to function.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] During installation, the user must consider an application's privileges and should not accept the installation if the requested rights are inconsistent.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] A user's phone can be protected through simple gestures and precautions, such as locking the smartphone when it is not in use, not leaving the device unattended, not blindly trusting applications, not storing sensitive data, or encrypting sensitive data that cannot be separated from the device.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] , it is recommended to "Restrict user and application access to hardware, such as the digital camera, GPS, Bluetooth interface, USB interface, and removable storage".
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This can include removing permissions and configurations for unused peripheral devices.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] smartphones come with a built-in encryption setting for securing all the information saved on your device.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This makes it difficult for a hacker to extract and decipher the information in case your device is compromised.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Settings → Security → Encrypt Phone + Encrypt SD Card.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Smartphones have significant memory capacity and can carry several gigabytes of data.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] The user must be careful about what data it carries and whether they should be protected (such as files containing bank information or business data).
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] The user must have the prudence to avoid the transmission of sensitive data on a smartphone, which can be easily stolen.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Furthermore, when a user gets rid of a device, they must be sure to remove all personal data first.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] These precautions reduce the ability for people or malicious applications to exploit a user's smartphone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] If users are careful, many attacks can be defeated, especially phishing and applications seeking only to obtain rights on a device.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] One form of mobile protection allows companies to control the delivery and storage of text messages, by hosting the messages on a company server, rather than on the sender or receiver's phone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] When certain conditions are met, such as an expiration date, the messages are deleted.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] The security mechanisms mentioned in this article are to a large extent inherited from knowledge and experience with computer security.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] The elements composing the two device types are similar, and there are common measures that can be used, such as antivirus software and firewalls.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] However, the implementation of these solutions is not necessarily possible (or is at least highly constrained) within a mobile device.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Furthermore, it is common that even if updates exist, or can be developed, they are not always deployed.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] For example, a user may not be aware of operating system updates; or a user may discover known vulnerabilities that are not corrected until the end of a long development cycle, which allows time to exploit the loopholes.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This category will contain traditional mobile operating systems like Android, iOS, Symbian OS, or Windows Phone.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] They will provide the traditional functionality and security of an OS to the applications.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This category features a secure kernel which will run in parallel with a fully featured Rich OS, on the same processor core.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] It will include drivers for the Rich OS ("normal world") to communicate with the secure kernel ("secure world").
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] The trusted infrastructure could include interfaces like the display or keypad to regions of PCI-E address space and memories.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] This environment will be made up of hardware and software.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] It helps control of access rights and houses sensitive applications, which need to be isolated from the Rich OS.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] It effectively acts as a firewall between the "normal world" and "secure world".
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] The SE consists of tamper-resistant hardware and associated software or separate isolated hardware.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] It can provide high levels of security and work in tandem with the TEE.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] The SE will be mandatory for hosting proximity payment applications or official electronic signatures.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] SE may connect, disconnect, block peripheral devices, and operate separate set of hardware.
[src:mobile-app-security/mobile-security-p02] Numerous security applications are available on app stores, providing protection from viruses and performing vulnerability assessment.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] In software development, **obfuscation** is the practice of creating source or machine code that is intentionally difficult for humans or computers to understand.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Similar to obfuscation in natural language, code obfuscation may involve using unnecessarily roundabout ways to write statements.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Programmers may obfuscate code to conceal its purpose, logic, or embedded values.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] The primary reasons for doing so are to prevent tampering, deter reverse engineering, or to create a puzzle or recreational challenge to deobfuscate the code, a challenge often included in crackmes.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] While obfuscation can be done manually, it is more commonly performed using obfuscators.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] The architecture and characteristics of some languages may make them easier to obfuscate than others.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] C, C++, and the Perl programming language are some examples of languages easy to obfuscate.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Haskell is also quite obfuscatable despite being quite different in structure.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] The properties that make a language obfuscatable are not immediately obvious.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Types of obfuscations include simple keyword substitution, use or non-use of whitespace to create artistic effects, and self-generating or heavily compressed programs.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] 3. double coding, which can be displaying code in poetry form or interesting shapes.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] More sophisticated techniques that obfuscate a program at the semantic level through program transformations also exist (rather than at the source level).
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] The following illustrates simple source-code obfuscation.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Both programs print the same output, but the second version is intentionally harder to understand.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] In the obfuscated version, meaningful variable names are removed and arithmetic expressions are rewritten in a less readable form, while preserving the program’s behavior.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] XOR encryption and Base64 encoding are two common methods used to hide malware from antivirus detection.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Both work by changing how malicious code appears in its file form, which prevents security software from recognizing dangerous patterns.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] In XOR obfuscation, an attacker chooses a secret key and applies the XOR bitwise operation to the malware binary.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] This transforms the executable into what looks like random data.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Function names in the import table vanish, PE headers become corrupted, and the entire file loses its structure.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] The obfuscated payload then gets embedded into a *dropper*, which is a normal-looking executable that contains the hidden malware as a resource or data section.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] When a user runs the dropper, it performs the XOR operation again with the same key to reconstruct the original malware, then either executes it directly from memory or writes it to disk before running it.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] This process removes several indicators that antivirus software relies on.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] The MZ header⁠‍—‍‌the 2-byte signature "MZ" which marks the beginning of every Windows executable‍—‍‌gets completely obscured by the XOR operation.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Security programs frequently scan for this two-byte signature when searching for embedded executables.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Base64 encoding achieves similar results through a different method: it converts binary data into ASCII text such that an executable file ends up looking like plain text (rather than like a program).
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Research from the 2020 Machine Learning Security Evasion Competition showed that these methods can bypass modern detection systems.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Participants used combinations of XOR encoding, Base64 encoding, and dead code insertion to evade all three competition models with fewer than five attempts per sample.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Entropy-based detection also failed, and in some cases Base64 encoding actually lowered the entropy compared to the original malware files.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] The simplicity of these techniques is what makes them particularly dangerous.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] XOR and Base64 encoding require only basic programming skills to implement, yet they proved effective against advanced machine learning classifiers.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] This has pushed security researchers toward new defenses, including automated XOR key recovery tools and deeper analysis of embedded resources in executable files.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] A variety of tools exist to perform or assist with code obfuscation.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] These include experimental research tools developed by academics, hobbyist tools, commercial products written by professionals, and open-source software.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Additionally, deobfuscation tools exist, aiming to reverse the obfuscation process.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] While most commercial obfuscation solutions transform either program source code or platform-independent bytecode, *i.e.* portable code (as used by Java and .NET), some also work directly on compiled binaries.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Writing and reading obfuscated source code can be a brain teaser.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] A number of programming contests reward the most creatively obfuscated code, such as the International Obfuscated C Code Contest and the Obfuscated Perl Contest.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Short obfuscated Perl programs may be used in signatures of Perl programmers, known as JAPHs ("Just another Perl hacker").
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Cryptographers have explored the idea of obfuscating code so that reverse-engineering the code is *cryptographically* hard.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] This is formalized in the many proposals for indistinguishability obfuscation, a cryptographic primitive that, if possible to build securely, would allow one to construct many other kinds of cryptography, including completely novel types that no one knows how to make.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Some anti-virus softwares, such as AVG AntiVirus, will alert their users when they land on a website with code that is manually obfuscated, as one of the purposes of obfuscation can be to hide malicious code.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] However, some developers may employ code obfuscation for the purpose of reducing file size or increasing security.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] The average user may not expect their antivirus software to provide alerts about an otherwise harmless piece of code, especially from trusted corporations, so such a feature may actually deter users from using legitimate software.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] Mozilla and Google disallow browser extensions containing obfuscated code in their browser (Firefox and Chrome, respectively) add-on stores.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] There has been debate on whether it is illegal to skirt copyleft software licenses by releasing source code in obfuscated form, such as in cases in which the author is less willing to make the source code available.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] The issue is addressed in the GNU General Public License by requiring the "preferred form for making modifications" to be made available.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] A decompiler is a tool that can reverse-engineer source code from an executable or library.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] This process is sometimes referred to as a man-in-the-end (mite) attack, inspired by the traditional "man-in-the-middle attack" in cryptography.
[src:mobile-app-security/obfuscation-software] The decompiled source code is often hard to read, containing random function and variable names, incorrect variable types, and logic that differs from the original source code due to compiler optimizations.
